<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-325-148  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 325 148.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  April 2 1990 v4 n13 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Air Force, Navy modify plans for aerial mission systems. (theNaval Air Systems Command's Tactical Aircraft Mission PlanningSystem and the Air Force Tactical Air Forces Advanced MissionPlanning System)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Poos, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Naval Air Systems Command will revise its Tactical AircraftMission Planning System (TAMPS) and the Air Force renames itsTactical Air Forces Advanced Mission Planning System the Air ForceAdvanced Mission Planning System (AFAMPS), both in an effort tobroaden applications for the programs across commands.andP;  The newTAMPS system will upgrade the system delivered by McDonnellDouglas Corp in 1985 and will cost about $12 million, the same asthe initial system; Marine Corp tactical aircraft, helicopters andsmart weapons would be included in the new system.andP;  AFAMPS willinclude planes in the Military Airlift Command and Strategic AirCommand in addition to tactical fighter/bomber aircraft; spendingfor the prototype phase of the program will be cut by more thanhalf from the original estimate of $100 million.andP;  TAMPS will letpilots and mission planners process large amounts of informationquickly, including terrain, weather, weapons and threat data.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AircraftCommand and Control SystemsPlanningDefense ContractsGovernment ContractsWeaponsMilitaryUnited States. Air ForceUnited States. Navy.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>